<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="91" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" box="[199,345,150,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,150,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Description.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" box="[199,608,186,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,186,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Male</emphasis>
(first description) (
<figureCitation box="[477,596,186,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[186,1396,197,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[179,1408,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (male). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Body in ventral view. C. Body in profile view. D. Head in front view. E. Mesosoma in lateral view. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Propodeum dorsal view. T1 and T2. I. T6 and T7. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Figs 2A–I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Measurements (in mm): Body length 7.8, forewing length 5.4, head height 2, head width 1.3, interantennal distance 0.3, antennocular distance 0.1, ocellocular distance 0.2, ocelloccipital distances 0.2, areola length 0.6, areola basal width 0.4, areola apical width 0.2, tegula length 1, and tegula middle width 0.5.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Colour: body metallic blue, except for tegula, legs, and mandible black; antenna brown; forewing extremely dark infumate, stigma dark; apical half of T7 rufous.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
Head: triangular, antenna very short and stout; clypeal anterior margin triangular; mandible bidentate; maxillary palpi large; front and vertex with very large contiguous punctures (
<figureCitation box="[900,990,438,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[164,1430,191,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[152,1437,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (female). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Head in front view. C. Body in ventral view. D. Body in profile view. E. Midtibial spurs. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Forewing. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637285/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
Mesosoma: pronotal carina complete, and well-developed, punctures large and contiguous as on front, lateral pronotum entirely and very coarsely reticulopunctate (
<figureCitation box="[763,852,510,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[186,1396,197,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[179,1408,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (male). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Body in ventral view. C. Body in profile view. D. Head in front view. E. Mesosoma in lateral view. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Propodeum dorsal view. T1 and T2. I. T6 and T7. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
); scutum between notauli coarsely reticulopunctate; mesopleuron with a well-defined carina, completely coarsely punctate with contiguous punctures; metanotum and scutellum with very coarse punctures similar to those on scutum; midtibia apically with two tibial spurs; hindtibia elongate with nearly parallel upper and lower margins; mid and hind femora cylindrical, inner face strongly convex, without a longitudinal ridge, with two spur, both relatively small, outer face with spines and very sparse hairs; tegula much elongated, auriform, almost twice as long as middle width; radius of forewing with an intercubital spur (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[186,1396,197,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[179,1408,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (male). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Body in ventral view. C. Body in profile view. D. Head in front view. E. Mesosoma in lateral view. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Propodeum dorsal view. T1 and T2. I. T6 and T7. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Figs. 2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[200,237,726,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[164,1430,191,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[152,1437,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (female). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Head in front view. C. Body in ventral view. D. Body in profile view. E. Midtibial spurs. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Forewing. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637285/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">3G</figureCitation>
); marginal cell of forewing completely closed; dorsal propodeum lateral to areola with three high, crooked longitudinal carinae as high as those of areola, areola tricarinate, median carina incomplete apically (
<figureCitation box="[1279,1369,762,788]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[186,1396,197,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[179,1408,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (male). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Body in ventral view. C. Body in profile view. D. Head in front view. E. Mesosoma in lateral view. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Propodeum dorsal view. T1 and T2. I. T6 and T7. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
); propodeum laterally with lower non-rugose part separated from upper part by a continuous groove; upper part entirely coarse rugose; propodeum posteriorly with very fine rugulae convergent on articulation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
Metasoma: T1 with a very strong transverse carina supported by many short longitudinal ridges; anterior aspect strongly declivous, with scattered primary punctures and dense, extremely fine micropunctures; terminal two-fifths of T1 completely impunctate (
<figureCitation box="[491,581,942,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[186,1396,197,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-18@2.[179,1408,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (male). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Body in ventral view. C. Body in profile view. D. Head in front view. E. Mesosoma in lateral view. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Propodeum dorsal view. T1 and T2. I. T6 and T7. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637283" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637283/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 2H</figureCitation>
); base of T2 with many short longitudinal ridges, three-fifths coarsely punctate and terminal two-fifths moderate-sized punctures; T3–T6 with moderate-sized punctures, uniform in size and distribution except apices which are polished impunctate for one-third to one-half punctate area; terga with sparse, elongate, dark brown hairs; pygidium with coarse ellipsoid and very regular punctures having a broad V-shaped termination; S5 simple, without denticle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" box="[199,436,1122,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1122,1148]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[302,424,1122,1148]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[164,1430,191,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[152,1437,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (female). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Head in front view. C. Body in ventral view. D. Body in profile view. E. Midtibial spurs. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Forewing. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637285/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 3A–E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" box="[199,736,1158,1185]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Same as male, except the following differences.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Measurements (in mm): Body length 9.5, forewing length 7.7, head height 2.2, head width 1.7, interantennal distance 0.3, antennocular distance 0.3, ocellocular distance 0.4, ocelloccipital distances 0.4, areola length 0.7, areola basal width 0.6, areola apical width 0.3, tegula length 1.4, tegula middle width 0.7.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
Clypeal anterior margin arcuate (
<figureCitation box="[569,656,1302,1328]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1869,1893]" captionTargetBox="[164,1430,191,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[152,1437,181,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Cyanotiphia ruficauda, Cameron (female). A. Body in dorsal view. B. Head in front view. C. Body in ventral view. D. Body in profile view. E. Midtibial spurs. F. Mid and hind femora. G. Forewing. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637285" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637285/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
); carinae lateral to areola connected by lesser cross ridges; last tergite and sternite entirely rufous; marginal cell of forewing almost closed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1024,1374,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,1401]" box="[199,1024,1374,1401]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1374,1400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Distribution.</emphasis>
Greater Sunda Islands (Borneo, 
<collectingRegion box="[719,769,1375,1401]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Java</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[824,919,1374,1400]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation box="[942,1007,1374,1400]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,2017,2041]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,1095,1986]" captionTargetId="figure-207@1.[151,1436,1085,1993]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution map of Cyanotiphia ruficauda Cameron, 1907" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637281/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="91">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
